{{one source|date=December 2012}} {{Infobox prepared food | name = Ohaw | image = Ainu ohaw.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = | alternate_name = Rur | country = [[Japan]] | region = | creator = | course = | type = [[Fish soup]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Stock (food)|Stock]], [[fish]] or animal bones, [[kelp]]; [[meat]], [[fish]], or [[vegetable]]s | variations = | calories = | other = }}
'''Ohaw''' or '''rur''' is a savory soup of the [[Ainu people]] of northern [[Japan]], flavored with [[fish]] or animal bones. [[Kelp]] is also used to add flavor to the [[stock (food)|stock]]. Unlike the majority of the traditional Japanese soups, the Ainu do not use [[miso]] or [[soy sauce]] in their soups.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/english/english.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 2, 2005 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050828185844/http://www.ainu-museum.or.jp/english/english.html |archivedate=August 28, 2005 }}</ref> The solid ingredients such as [[meat]], [[fish]], [[vegetable]]s and/or wild edible plants are added to the stock.
==Variants== * cep ohaw - salmon soup * kam ohaw - meat soup * yuk ohaw - venison soup * [[pukusa]] ohaw - pukusa soup * pukusakina ohaw - anemone soup
